sols:
For part (a), we seek to solve the system of congruences given by

\begin{align*}
5 & \equiv 4a + b \mod{26} \\
6 & \equiv 19a + b \mod{26}
\end{align*}

Subtracting the two equations yields

\begin{align*}
1 & \equiv 15a \mod{26} 
\end{align*}

Thus we need to find the inverse of 15 modulo 26. To do this we use the
Euclidean Algorithm.

\begin{align*}
26 &= 15(1) + 11\\
15 &= 11(1) + 4\\
11 &= 4(2) +3\\
4 &= 3(1) + 1
\end{align*}

and back substituting gives

\begin{align*}
1 &= 4 - 3(1)\\
1 &= 4 - (11-4(2))(1)\\
1 &= 4(3) - 11(1)\\
1 &= (15-11(1))(3) - 11(1)\\
1 &= 15(3)-11(4)\\
1 &= 15(3)-(26-15(1))(4)\\
1 &= 15(7)-26(4)\\
\end{align*}

and so an inverse of 15 modulo 26 is given by 7. Thus as
$\displaystyle 1 \equiv 15a \mod{26}$, we have that
$\displaystyle 7 \equiv a \mod{26}$. Plugging back into the original
equation gives $\displaystyle 5 \equiv 4a + b \equiv 4(7) + b \mod{26}$
and isolating for \emph{b} gives the value of 3 and so the encryption
key is $\displaystyle K_{E} = (26,7,3)$

For part (b), we seek to solve

\begin{align*}
4 & \equiv 5c + d \mod{26} \\
19 & \equiv 6c + d \mod{26}
\end{align*}

Subtracting these two equations gives
$\displaystyle 15 \equiv c \mod{26}$. Thus as
$\displaystyle 4 \equiv 5c + d \equiv 5(15) + d \equiv 75 + d \equiv -3 + d  \mod{26}$
(so \emph{d} is 7), we have that the decryption key is given by
$\displaystyle K_{D} = (26,15,7)$.

